I am tinkering with exposing an existing dictionary with data to Python. My code is pretty simple:

```C++
#include <map>
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

std::map<std::string, std::string> data = {
	{"key", "value"},
	{"key2", "value2"},
};

namespace {
  py::dict buildPythonDict() {
    py::dict results;

    for (const auto i: data) {
     results[py::cast(i.first)] = py::cast(i.second);
    }
    return results;
  }

  const auto py_data = buildPythonDict();
}


void expose(py::module &m) {
	m.attr("DATA") = py_data;
}
```

I was a little surprised by needing to use `py::cast()` there since I was expecting automatic conversion, but that's no big deal. What is really unexpected is that when you import the resulting module and then immediately exit Python it will segfault:

```
>>> import mymodule
>>> <ctrl-d>
Thread 0 Crashed:: Dispatch queue: com.apple.main-thread
0   org.python.python             	0x0000000108ada1c5 dict_dealloc + 40
1   stylist.cpython-36m-darwin.so 	0x000000010909b2cb pybind11::dict::~dict() + 27 (pytypes.h:1064)
2   libsystem_c.dylib             	0x00007fffb3853178 __cxa_finalize_ranges + 332
3   libsystem_c.dylib             	0x00007fffb38534b2 exit + 55
4   libdyld.dylib                 	0x00007fffb37be23c start + 8
```

I am struggling to understand exactly what is going on in snippets of code like this (taken from the documentation):

```c++
py::class_<Example>(m, "Example")
    .def("__init__",
        [](Example &instance, int arg) {
            new (&instance) Example(arg);
        }
    );
```

I understand that the intent here is to call placement new into the memory area of ``instance`` to construct the ``Example`` object with the provided argument ``arg``. My first question is: how is the reference ``Example &instance`` obtained? I am familiar with the use of, e.g., aligned storage + placement new on a ``void *`` after a couple of ``static_cast``s, but I am wondering how it has been implemented in pybind11 since it is using reference semantics.

Secondly, what happens if the constructor throws? Imagine something like this:

```c++
py::class_<Example>(m, "Example")
    .def("__init__",
        [](Example &instance, int arg) {
            new (&instance) Example(arg);
            throw std::runtime_error("");
        }
    );
```

Or imagine even that the ``throw`` is placed before the placement new call. What is it going to happen in that case? Is pybind11 going to call the destructor of ``Example``? Can it detect if the C++ constructor has been called or not?

This seems to be a worse issue in the pickling support:

```c++
    .def("__setstate__", [](Pickleable &p, py::tuple t) {
        if (t.size() != 2)
            throw std::runtime_error("Invalid state!");

        /* Invoke the in-place constructor. Note that this is needed even
           when the object just has a trivial default constructor */
        new (&p) Pickleable(t[0].cast<std::string>());

        /* Assign any additional state */
        p.setExtra(t[1].cast<int>());
    });
```

Here the C++ constructor of ``Pickleable`` may or may not be called depending on the content of ``t``.

Am I missing something obvious?

